What are immutable objects?
Immutable objects are objects whose state cannot be changed after they are created. Once an object is initialized, its data remains constant throughout its lifetime.
For example, String, wrapper classes like Integer, and classes from the Java Time API like LocalDateTime are immutable.

Any modification to an immutable object results in the creation of a new object instead of changing the existing one. This makes immutable objects inherently thread-safe.”

🔍 Simple Example
String s = "Java";
s.concat(" World");

System.out.println(s);
👉 Output: Java

✔️ Because:
concat() creates a new object
Original object is unchanged
