What happens if hashCode is same but equals is false?”
Same hashCode and different equals means collision. HashMap stores both objects in the same bucket and uses equals() to identify them separately.”
If two objects have the same hashCode but equals() returns false, they will be stored in the same bucket but as different entries.

HashMap uses hashCode() to find the bucket and equals() to differentiate keys within the bucket.

So, both objects will coexist without any issue.
“Why 8 as threshold?”
“Threshold 8 is used in Java 8 HashMap to convert linked list into Red-Black Tree for better performance during heavy collisions.”

